title: Karen Durbin

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Karen Durbin
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning or describing Karen Durbin, who edited The Village Voice. She was born in 1944 and died April 15, 2025. Her death was widely covered in the press: 

https://www.nytimes.com/2025/04/23/business/media/karen-durbin-dead.html

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies. This is also to include any responsive records held in offsite locations, such as the Alexandria Records Center. Please include both investigatory and non-investigatory records in your search.

If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

I am a member of the news media and request classification as such. I have previously written about the government and its activities, and am currently a reporter of The Boston Globe.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Alexa Gagosz

title: FOIA/CPRA Submission: Ventura County Sheriff Assault Response – Block & Santos (April 2025)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: FOIA/CPRA Submission: Ventura County Sheriff Assault Response – Block & Santos (April 2025)
communications.communication:
To:
Ventura County Sheriff’s Office
Public Records Unit
800 S. Victoria Avenue
Ventura, CA 93009
Email: info.vcsd@ventura.org

From:
Jordan Lassiter

Subject: CPRA Request – Assault Incident Involving Joshua Block and Santos (April 23, 2025)

⸻

Dear Custodian of Records,

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act (CPRA), Government Code §§ 6250–6276.48, and California Constitution Article I, § 3(b), I respectfully request access to public records related to an assault (non-domestic) incident involving Joshua Block and an individual identified as Santos, which occurred in Ventura County on or about April 23, 2025, at approximately 7:00 PM (19:00 hours).

⸻

Records Requested:
	1.	Body-Worn Camera Footage
	•	All body-worn camera (BWC) recordings from deputies who responded to the incident.
	2.	911 Call Audio and Transcripts
	•	All emergency call recordings and transcripts related to this incident.
	3.	CAD / Dispatch Logs
	•	Full dispatch data including unit assignments, timestamps, and call notes.
	4.	Incident and Arrest Reports
	•	All reports created in connection with this assault, including officer narratives, witness statements, investigative reports, and any arrest documentation.
	5.	Photographs or Supplemental Evidence
	•	Any digital evidence, such as photographs or surveillance obtained during the response.
	6.	Preservation Notice
	•	I formally request that all potentially responsive records be preserved, including digital and metadata. Alteration or deletion of such records after receipt of this request may constitute a violation of Gov. Code § 6200 and legal precedent such as People v. Superior Court (Barrett), 80 Cal.App.4th 1305 (2000).

⸻

Legal Justification:
	•	Gov. Code § 6254(f) provides for public access to law enforcement response records including arrest information, time, location, and substance of calls.
	•	AB 748 (Gov. Code § 6254(f)(4)) mandates the disclosure of body-worn camera footage in incidents involving the use of force or where the public interest in disclosure clearly outweighs any investigatory need for withholding.
	•	Courts in CBS v. Block, 42 Cal.3d 646 (1986) and Haynie v. Superior Court, 26 Cal.4th 1061 (2001) require narrowly tailored justifications for any denial or redaction of law enforcement records.
	•	The public’s right to information that fosters accountability is further supported by Brady v. Maryland, 373 U.S. 83 (1963), and People v. Superior Court (Johnson), 61 Cal.4th 696 (2015).

⸻

Format & Fee Waiver Request:

Please provide all records in electronic format (PDF, MP4, etc.). I also request a waiver of fees under Gov. Code § 6253(e), as this request is made for public interest purposes and not commercial use.

If any fees are expected, I request a written estimate before incurring any charges.

⸻

Please acknowledge receipt of this request and provide an estimated date for completion in accordance with Gov. Code § 6253(c). I am available to assist in clarifying or narrowing this request if necessary.

Thank you for your time and commitment to transparency.

Sincerely,
Jordan Lassiter

title: Digital Public Library of America communications

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Digital Public Library of America communications
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

As background information, on 4/22/2022, I submitted a request with tracking number  NARA-NGC-2022-001048. I requested all emails to or from NARA from the external domain @dp.la. This was eventually rejected as overly broad—which I object to, as my belief is it would only have amounted to a few dozen emails, and I was given no answer to my follow up to understand the difficulty. In any case, in the rejection from NARA, the following was stated:

"However, the requester needs to be specific in identifying the type of record; the topic or subject covered by the record, and an approximate date for the record. The FOIA does not require agencies to conduct research, answer questions, or analyze data. Your request does not give the information necessary to identify potentially Federal responsive records. Could you please provide a specific department (within NARA) that you believe may have communicated with the organization cited in your FOIA request?"

In response, I would like to narrow/reformulate my request to emails with specific keywords found only in emails to/from specific NARA staff email addresses, within a limited date range. Please see this more limited list of 10 NARA employees:

* Hannah Bergman <hannah.bergman@nara.gov>
* Jason Clingerman <jason.clingerman@nara.gov>
* David Ferriero <david.ferriero@nara.gov> or <archivistoftheunitedstates@nara.gov>
* Valorie Findlater <valorie.findlater@nara.gov>
* Carol Lagundo <carol.lagundo@nara.gov>
* Maureen MacDonald <maureen.macdonald@nara.gov>
* Gary M. Stern <garym.stern@nara.gov>
* Debra Wall <debra.wall@nara.gov>
* Andrew Wilson <andrew.wilson@nara.gov>
* Pamela Wright <pamela.wright@nara.gov>

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. All emails, including attachments, sent to or from the above listed NARA staff members, from the period of August 1, 2019 to December 31 , 2020 which contain the terms "Digital Public Library of America" or "DPLA".

2. Google Chat messages from the same individuals and same time frame with the matching search terms, as well as the 10 messages occurring before or after them (to capture the context).

Because NARA is a member of the association being searched for, I have reason to believe there will be responsive records. I do not believe the number will be excessive, because this is not a major component of NARA's work, but if you still believe the request needs to be narrowed, despite the very specific ways in which I have already given parameters for the document search, then I would appreciate additional details as to what makes it excessive (e.g. if a search was done and what the number of emails was).

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

TR
